AB It has been suggested that evaluations may be based on a
   "How-do-I-feel-about-it?" heuristic, which involves holding a
   representation of the target in mind and inspecting feelings that this
   representation may elicit. Previous studies have shown that reliance on
   such feelings depends on whether or not they are believed to be
   representative of the target. This article argues that reliance on
   feelings also depends on whether feelings toward the target are regarded
   as relevant. Consistent with this thesis, findings from three
   experiments indicate that reliance on the "How-do-I-feel-about-it?"
   heuristic is more likely when the decision maker has consummatory as
   opposed to instrumental motives. Results also suggest that subtle
   feelings toward the target are indeed instantiated in the process, and
   that the process may be more likely among individuals with a propensity
   to process information in a visual and sensory manner.
